  "The area formula Area = (1/2)ab*sin(C) uses two sides and their included angle. This is useful when the height of the triangle is not directly known.": "",
  "In a triangle, a = 7, b = 10, and C = 60 degrees. Using the Law of Cosines, what is c^2?": "",
  "79": "",
  "149": "",
  "49": "",
  "219": "",
  "c^2 = a^2 + b^2 - 2ab*cos(C) = 49 + 100 - 2(7)(10)*cos(60) = 149 - 140(0.5) = 149 - 70 = 79.": "",
  "When should you use the Law of Cosines instead of the Law of Sines?": "",
  "When the triangle is equilateral": "",
  "Only for right triangles": "",
  "When you know two sides and the included angle (SAS) or all three sides (SSS)": "",
  "When you know two angles and a side": "",
  "The Law of Cosines is used when you know SAS (two sides and the included angle) or SSS (all three sides). The Law of Sines works better with AAS, ASA, or SSA configurations.": "",
